  "text": "A total of 73% of cancer survivors had full RTW that is at equal earnings as before sickness absence; 13% were granted disability pension, 8% resigned their job, and 6% died within 2 years after diagnosis. Full RTW rates of employees diagnosed with genital cancer or skin cancer were comparable to those of employees who were absent from work due to non-malignant chronic disorders. The rates of full RTW were considerably lower in patients diagnosed with breast cancer, gastro-intestinal cancer, lung cancer, and blood malignancies and were in line with cancer survival data in European adults [CITATION_1] . Employees with lung cancer were absent from work for the longest period of time (median 490 days) and had the worst RTW prognosis. Women aged X35 years and men aged X55 years with genital cancer had a longer time to full RTW compared with survivors of genital cancer agedo35 years. Women with blood malignancies had a longer time to full RTW than men with blood malignancies.",
